 next on the table. You also buy something less obvious: time, because the negotiation draws curious eyes and slows the bandits’ informants who would have signaled your approach. When you roll out again the road hums a different note, and while the danger has not lessened, the air no longer feels like a contract weighted entirely against your breath.\"},\n        {\"id\": \"C4\", \"title\": \"Sanctify the Axles: Solace Oils and Quiet Wheels\", \"text\": \"Before the moon’s pull can turn the glass petulant, you open the Solace Enzyme Kit and begin the slow, reverent work of wicking oil into every joint that might complain. You teach junior hands how to brush in circles that coax instead of bruise, and you send a whisper down each spoke that reminds it of its task and its companions. The smell of herbs rises like a shaded bath in midsummer, cooling tempers and loosening fear where it has knotted tight in shoulders and jaws. You finish with absorbent moss pads beneath the most temperamental axles, a gift to the road that says you are willing to meet it halfway. It feels like an indulgence in a world of ration, but you know the arithmetic of mercy often outlasts the arithmetic of austerity.\", \"outcome\": \"When the first crack sounds, it is no more than a glass’s click against a table, and the wagons glide over as if shod in patience. The second crack is a grumble, and the moss pads drink the vibration so thoroughly that even the mules flick only one ear. You pay in time and in oil, and a few jars will not be replaced quickly, but the cost is less than a broken axle or a crushed foot would have written into your day. The crews sleep easier in snatches, and even those who distrust Solace alchemy admit that the wheels have forgotten how to scream. At the Crucible gates a foreman runs a practiced hand along the hubs and grunts approval, and the log you sign feels less like a ledger and more like a lullaby laid down in ink.\"\n        }\n      ],\n      \"connections\": {